'''Ageometresia''' or '''ageometria''' is a word describing a defect in a work of [[geometry]].<ref name="c1728">{{citation|title=Encyclopaedia Perthensis; or Universal dictionary of the arts, sciences, literature, &c. intended to supersede the use of other books of reference|volume=1|publisher=John Brown|date=1816|page=308|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vvVPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA308}}.</ref>
An early usage of the word was in writings of [[François Viète]] on [[Copernicus]].<ref name="rosen">{{citation|title=On the revolutions: Foundations of natural history|volume=1|series=Complete Works of Nicolas Copernicus|first=Edward|last=Rosen|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|date=1992|isbn=978-0-8018-4515-4|page=334}}.</ref> As another instance, [[Johannes Kepler]], having no direct and geometrical method of finding certain matters in his [[Kepler's laws of planetary motion|elliptical theory]], namely how to calculate the [[true anomaly]] from the [[mean anomaly]], has been charged by others with ageometresia.<ref>{{citation|title=Indian science and technology in the eighteenth century: some contemporary European accounts|author=Dharampal|publisher=Impex India|date=1971|page=58}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|first=Ephraim|last=Chambers|authorlink=Ephraim Chambers|title=[[Cyclopaedia, or an Universal Dictionary of Arts and Sciences]]|date=1728|page=45}}.</ref>
Although Viète wrote in [[Latin language|Latin]], the word "ageometresia" is Greek,<ref name="rosen"/> and the same Greek word has also subsequently been used by writers in English.<ref name="c1728"/> As well as its usage to indicate faults in the works of professional mathematicians, "ageometria" has also been used to describe a form of [[dyscalculia]], a disability that prevents students from understanding geometry.<ref>{{citation|title=Bases of Language Intervention|volume=1|series=Language intervention series|first1=Richard L.|last1=Schiefelbusch|first2=Marilyn|last2=Barket|publisher=University Park Press|date=1978|page=23|isbn=978-0-8391-1197-9}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Principles of Child Neurology|first=Bruce O.|last=Berg|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]]|date=1996|isbn=978-0-07-005193-5|page=362}}.</ref>
