A '''biconcave disc''' — also referred to as a '''discocyte'''<ref name="kuchelfackerell">{{Cite journal |last1=Kuchel |first1=Philip W. |last2=Fackerell |first2=Edward D. |year=1999 |title=Parametric-equation representation of biconcave erythrocytes |journal=Bulletin of Mathematical Biology |language=en |volume=61 |issue=2 |pages=209–220 |doi=10.1006/bulm.1998.0064 |pmid=17883208 |s2cid=39585695 |issn=1522-9602 }}</ref> — is a geometric shape resembling an [[oblate spheroid]] with two [[Concavity|concavities]] on the top and on the bottom.

Biconcave discs appear in the study of [[cell biology]], where it is [[meta-stable]], and involves the continuous adjustment of the asymmetric transbilayer lipid distribution, which is correlated with [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]] depletion.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Pages |first1=Guilhem |last2=Yau |first2=Tsz W. |last3=Kuchel |first3=Philip W. |date=2010 |title=Erythrocyte shape reversion from echinocytes to discocytes: Kinetics via fast-measurement NMR diffusion-diffraction |journal=Magnetic Resonance in Medicine |language=en |volume=64 |issue=3 |pages=645–652 |doi=10.1002/mrm.22457 |pmid=20806372 }}</ref>

==Mathematical model==

A biconcave disc can be described mathematically by
:<math>z(r) = D \sqrt{1 - \frac{4r^2}{D^2}} \left(a_0 + \frac{a_1 r^2}{D^2} + \frac{a_2 r^4}{D^4} \right)</math>
where {{math|z(r)}} is the height of the surface as a function of radius {{math|r}}, {{math|D}} is the diameter of the disc, and {{math|a_0, a_1, a_2}} are coefficients describing the shape.  The above model describes a smooth surface; actual cells can be much more irregular.

==Biology==
[[Erythrocytes]] are in the shape of a biconcave disc.<ref name="kuchelfackerell" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Muñoz |first1=Sagrario |last2=Sebastián |first2=José L. |last3=Sancho |first3=Miguel F. |last4=Álvarez |first4=Gabriel |date=2014-03-01 |title=Elastic energy of the discocyte–stomatocyte transformation |journal=Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - Biomembranes |volume=1838 |issue=3 |pages=950–956 |doi=10.1016/j.bbamem.2013.10.020 |pmid=24192054 |issn=0005-2736 }}</ref>

